      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If temperature or moisture content is off, the Maillard reaction can be significantly disrupted. If the temperature is too high, it can lead to over-caramelization, resulting in burnt, bitter flavors and a charred texture. Conversely, if the temperature is too low, the reaction may not occur at all, or may occur too slowly, leading to a less intense flavor development. Moisture content also plays a crucial role, as too much moisture can prevent the reaction from occurring, while too little can cause the reaction to occur too quickly, leading to a bitter or burnt flavor.",
